data.content:
Here's what's happening and how to fix it:

## The Problem

C# 14's new **span overload resolution** causes `array.Contains(num)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` (which takes `ReadOnlySpan<T>`) instead of `Enumerable.Contains` (which takes `IEnumerable<T>`). Expression trees **cannot represent span-based methods**, so this throws at runtime.

## The Fix

Force the compiler to bind to `Enumerable.Contains` by any of these approaches:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three prevent the span overload from being selected, keeping the expression tree valid.
